\begin_layout Section
How Effective is Word-of-Mouth?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
xyz
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Customer Reviews
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Online Conversations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Besides customer reviews, another important type of online WOM that is relevant
 to marketing is in the form of online conversations among customers.
 Online conversations involve customers use online social media platforms
 such as Twitter or Facebook to communicate and discuss a common topic related
 to the firm, such as its brand or product.
 As discussed earlier, we decide that these two types of WOM should be evaluated
 separately.
 One key difference between reviews and online conversations is that conversatio
ns by definition have an interactive and social component, and can happen
 both after and 
\emph on
before
\emph default
 the consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conversations among customers used to be confined within offline small social
 circles.
 Such conversations, however, have become more prevalently online with the
 ascendency of social media platforms.
 For a more focused discussion below, we are especially interested in the
 effectiveness of online interactions on social media platforms such as
 Twitter and Facebook.
 We also consider tweeting, retweeting, forwarding, commenting, and other
 activities on these platforms all fit into the loosely defined 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

online conversations.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To answer the question about how effective online conversations are, it
 would be useful to first consider how we can measure the effectiveness
 of online conversations.
 In both practice and academia, many focus on measuring the volume of online
 conversations in the context of social media (e.g., the number of posts and
 comments about a firm and its products on Twitter or Facebook).
 However, in our opinion, the most straightforward and objective metric
 is the incremental demand or sales caused by online conversations.
 Especially, the mere volume of online conversations is mostly an intermediary
 objective, while the ultimate goal of the firm is to enhance its demand.
 Below we will introduce a few recent studies that pay extra attention to
 the measurement challenges aforementioned and carefully rely on exogenous
 data variations to infer the effectiveness of online conversations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Online Conversations' Effect on Sales
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Can online conversations affect sales? Based on the extant research, the
 answer is a qualified yes, and the effect is potentially moderate in size.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It is difficult to gauge the cost of managing online conversations.
 Accordingly, we choose not to assess the ROI of online conversations.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many studies proclaim high effectiveness of online conversation on boosting
 demand and leading to additional sales, and often laud it as a more effective
 marketing tool than traditional advertising.
 For example, the meta-analysis of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "you_et_al_2010"

\end_inset

 documents an astonishing average elasticity of online WOM as 0.2.
 Furthermore, several studies which specifically zoom in on online conversations
 on social media websites report even higher level of elasticities (e.g.,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "sonnier_et_al2011"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Dhar_Chang_2009"

\end_inset

).
 However, empirical studies using observational data of online WOM and demand
 are often subject to the measurement challenges mentioned in Section XX,
 and tend to overestimate the effect size.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More researchers have started to pay attention to the measurement bias problem,
 though the research on the topic is still sparse because online conversations
 are not under the direct control of firms.
 Several recent studies more carefully explore exogenous variations in online
 conversations and the consequent impact on product demand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Seiler_et_al_2017"

\end_inset

 study the effect of customer microblogging on TV viewership, which is essential
ly the demand for TV shows.
 Due to some political reason, the Chinese government temporarily shut down
 the microblogging platform Sina Weibo in 2012, which was the most important
 and popular social media website in China at the time.
 The authors rely on this exogenous shock that reduces the amount of online
 conversations to study the effect on TV viewership.
 They show that the reduction of customer conversations does lead to lower
 consumption of TV shows, but the effect size is at a fairly moderate level
 of 0.016, which is several order lower than previous studies (e.g., the average
 of 0.2 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "you_et_al_2010"

\end_inset

).
 The paper by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "lovett_staelin"

\end_inset

, although not rely on experimental data, also finds online social media
 and WOM have a positive impact on TV viewership with a moderate effect
 size of 0.04, less effective than advertising.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a parallel study by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "gong_et_al_2015"

\end_inset

, which also studies the effect of microblogging on TV viewership, the authors
 execute a field experiment to exogenously vary the amount of firm's tweets
 and also randomly hire influential users to retweets about TV shows.
 They demonstrate that the amount of firm microblogging and influential
 users' retweets can in fact boost viewership (demand).
 We note that tweets from a firm's official account may not be fully qualified
 as online conversations by customers.
 However, the retweets from (hired) influentials, and potentially additional
 comments and retweets from their followers, can be labeled as online conversati
ons, which may also play a role in enhancing demand.
 In a different context of political campaigning, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Petrova_et_al_2016"

\end_inset

 consider the effect of a politician opening an official twitter account
 on campaign donations from supporters.
 The authors rely on the variations of timing of opening the twitter account
 and different penetration rates of twitter across markets, demonstrating
 that the official twitter account opening consequently increases donations,
 and the effect size is comparable to political advertising.
 Again, the study focuses on the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

official
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 accounts and does not directly speak to online conversations by customers.
 But the presence of official accounts may generate additional online conversati
ons among customers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In conclusion, based on a few recent papers which use more reliable exogenous
 variations in data to infer the effect of online conversations on demand,
 online conversations do have a moderate positive impact on demand, and
 the effectiveness is slightly less or comparable to advertising.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Why does Word-of-Mouth Marketing Work?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
