\begin_layout Subsection
Online Conversations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the ease of exposition, we contruct our discussion of the mechanisms
 of online conversations on demand using the conceptual framework proposed
 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bagwell_2007"

\end_inset

 for analyzing advertising's impact, which are information, persuasion,
 and complementarity between online conversations and product consumption.
 Although online conversations differ from traditional advertising, these
 three possible channels may be generalized to any kind of information provision
, also including online conversations.
 Informative effects can arise when online conversations among customers
 generate or disseminate product/brand information that the customers value,
 or purely remind customers about the product.
 Persuasive effects may enhance customers' preference towards the product,
 even without delivering information.
 Lastly, complementarity between online conversations and product consumption
 may happen if customers derive a higher utility from the product consumption
 if they can participate in the online conversations with others who share
 the same interest in the product.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The information and persuation effects of advertising has long been established
 in the literature.
 It is reasonable to expect online conversations may function in a similar
 fashion.
 In fact, in the paper by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "gong_et_al_2015"

\end_inset

 discussed earlier, the authors demonstrate that online conversations may
 indeed increase demand by informing or persuading customers about the product.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The study cannot distinguish the informative and persuasive effects.
 To the best of our knowledge, there is no study with field data that is
 able to convincingly separate the two mechanisms.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In the study, the authors show that firm's tweets with detailed information
 about the product, when being retweeted by influential users, have a strong
 impact of boosting demand.
 The effect of influential users' retweets become even stronger when their
 followers further retweet the content.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The third mechanism, the complementarity between conversations and product
 consumption, has only received limited attention until recently, partially
 because of limitation in data availability when conversations in the past
 were mainly offline and unobserved.
  In the context of advertising, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "becker_murphy1993"

\end_inset

 propose a theory where consumption of a product and watching the product's
 ads are complements to one another.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
In a recent study by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "tuchman_et_al_2015"

\end_inset

, the authors empirically show such a relationship between product consumption
 and ads watching.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In the context of online conversations, this complementarity mechanism
 is potentially more important because the participation in conversations
 about the product is arguably a more proactive and conscious decision than
 watching an ad.
 Recently, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Seiler_et_al_2017"

\end_inset

 demonstrate such complementarity effects also exist for online conversations.
 Using TV viewership (demand) and online microblogging data, the authors
 delve into the timing of the online conversations to the airing of TV shows.
 In particular, they show that conversations 
\emph on
after
\emph default
 a show's airing significantly affect the viewership.
 Intuitively, this finding implies that online conversations have functioned
 through the complementarity channel because, for informative and persuasive
 effects to work, the conversations have to happen 
\emph on
before
\emph default
 the broadcasting of the shows.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "gilchrist_sands_jpe"

\end_inset

 also show a similar complementarity effect of conversations on increasing
 movie box office sales.
 Though in their paper, the conversations can happen both online and offline.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
How can Firms Influence WOM Generation? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Online Reviews
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Online Conversations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While it is relatively easy to collect data on the volume of online conversation
s and its changes over time, it is tricky in understanding what actually
 drives the changes.
 For example, what types of content are more likely be shared among users
 in their conversations, and what types of individuals on social media platforms
 are more likely to share or forward content?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A number of studies have investigated how content of online conversations
 may affect the spread and hence enhance the overall volume of online conversati
ons.
 For example, through a series of studies, Berger and coauthors evaluate
 what content and products are more likely to be discussed on social network.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "berger2011"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "berger_milkman"

\end_inset

 suggest content or products that result in certain emotions (e.g., anxiety
 or amusement) are more likely to lead to more social sharing and online
 conversations.
 Such emotions are often associated with high level of awareness, alert,
 or attention of customers.
 In contrast, some other emotions, such as sadness, are less likely to lead
 to more social sharing and online conversations.
 In another study, using both field experiments and lab experiments, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "berger_schwartz"

\end_inset

 show that, on one hand, interesting products may generate more immediate
 conversations, but the attention may diminish soon.
 In the long run, these products receive less ongoing discussion over time.
 On the other hand, products that are more publicly visible enjoy a more
 sustainable WOM trend among customers.
 Using twitter data, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "zhang_2017"

\end_inset

 further highlight the importance of fit between message content and the
 interest of the user.
 When the content of a message fits a user's interest, which is identified
 using the user's past tweets, the message is more often rebroadcasted by
 the user.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another stream of research consider the question of how to identify the
 types of users who are more crucial in driving the volume of online conversatio
ns.
 For example, since the seminal work by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Katz_Lazarsfeld_1955"

\end_inset

, there are abundant studies that emphasize the importance of influential
 users' impact on others in the network (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "harikesh_2010"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "IVV_2011"

\end_inset

).
 It is intuitive to generalize the argument that on social media platforms
 influential users may affect the broadcasting decisions of others in their
 network.
 As a result, some studies that focus on identifying the influential users
 and users' susceptibility to influence from others (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "trusov_2010"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "zhang_2017"

\end_inset

).
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We should note that, as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "watts_dodds"

\end_inset

 argue, whether influential individuals are more crucial in online WOM is
 still debatable – A large cluster of easily influenced individuals may
 be more important than influential users.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One problematic approach is to directly gauge which types or groups of customers
 have more activities on social media.
 As discussed in Section XX, such an approach can be biased and often overestima
te the roles of certain groups of customers in enhancing online conversations.
 For example, suppose a firm released a new product and subsequently observed
 there was a large uptick in online conversations originated from some certain
 geographic areas.
 It happened to be the case that, due to limited inventory, the product
 was only initially rolled out in those areas.
 It would be erroneous to draw the inference that customers in those areas
 were more crucial in driving online conversations about the product.
 To avoid such incorrect conclusions, many studies rely on exogenous variations
 in data to derive inference.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "aral_walker"

\end_inset

, for example, use a large scale of field experiment on Facebook to investigate
 which types of customers are more likely to influence or be influenced
 on a social network.
 They randomly choose recipients out of a representative sample of 1.3 million
 Facebook users to receive messages from their friends about a product.
 They then monitor the adoption behavior of these users as well as collect
 demographic information of these users and of those from whom they receive
 the messages.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
While the exact key performance indicator (KPI) or outcome variable in this
 study is the adoption of a product instead of the increase in conversation
 volume, the product can be easily conceptualized as online conversation
 such as a tweet.
 Correspondingly, the adoption of the product is the rebroadcasting of the
 tweet.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 They find that older users are less susceptible than their younger counterparts
, women are less influential than men, but can influence men more than they
 do on other women, and married individuals are the least likely to be influence
d.
 Interestingly, influential users are less susceptible than non-influential
 users and they are more likely to cluster together in the network.
 This finding suggests that the spread of products or message in a network
 may crucially depend on influential people with influential friends.
\end_layout

